<Layout metadata={metadata}>
  <article class="max-w-2xl mx-auto px-6 py-16">

    <header class="mb-12">
      <p class="text-[11px] font-semibold tracking-[0.15em] uppercase mb-3" style="color:#059669;">NinjaTrader 8 · Behavioral Risk Control</p>
      <h1 class="text-4xl md:text-5xl font-bold text-zinc-900 leading-tight tracking-tight mb-5">
        Overtrading prevention in NinjaTrader 8
      </h1>
      <p class="text-lg text-zinc-500 leading-relaxed">
        Overtrading rarely feels like overtrading while it is happening. It presents as urgency — the sense that
        the next trade is the one that will recover the session. The position sizing and the frequency both increase
        before the trader is aware that the pattern has changed.
      </p>
    </header>

    <div class="prose prose-zinc max-w-none prose-p:text-[17px] prose-p:leading-[1.85] prose-headings:font-bold prose-headings:text-zinc-900 prose-h2:text-[1.35rem] prose-h2:mt-10 prose-h2:mb-3 prose-hr:border-zinc-200 prose-hr:my-10">

      <h2>What overtrading actually is — and is not</h2>
      <p>
        Overtrading is not simply "trading a lot." A high-frequency scalper who executes 40 trades per session
        by plan is not overtrading. Overtrading is when entry frequency exceeds your own established norm as a
        response to session conditions — typically following losses, missed trades, or periods of range-bound
        chop that produce consecutive small losses.
      </p>
      <p>
        The behavioral mechanism is the same as revenge trading but operates at a lower intensity and higher
        frequency. Rather than a single large retaliation trade, it produces a stream of lower-conviction entries,
        each one slightly less disciplined than the one before. The cumulative cost is often larger than the
        single revenge trade it mimics.
      </p>

      <h2>Why daily trade limits are not sufficient</h2>
      <p>
        The most common countermeasure is a hard daily trade count limit. Stop trading after 10 trades. After
        20 trades. After 5 losses. These rules are useful as a starting point but have a structural weakness:
        they impose a fixed threshold on a behavioral problem that is not fixed.
      </p>
      <p>
        On a day where the market is offering genuine setups and the trader is executing at their best, a
        hard trade count limit imposes unnecessary constraint. On a day where entry frequency has doubled
        in the second half of the session following a loss sequence, the limit may not be reached until
        significant damage is already done.
      </p>
      <p>
        A dynamic threshold — one that responds to the actual rate of change in behavior, not just the
        cumulative total — is a more precise instrument.
      </p>

      <h2>How Meridian's Overtrading Pace signal works</h2>
      <p>
        Meridian computes entry frequency across a rolling window and compares it to the trader's own
        historical session average. The <strong>Overtrading Pace</strong> signal activates when the current
        entry rate exceeds the trader's personal baseline by a configured multiple — not when it exceeds
        an arbitrary population average.
      </p>
      <p>
        This matters because individual trading styles vary substantially. A scalper who normally averages
        one entry every 2 minutes is not overtrading at 1 minute intervals the same way a position trader
        who normally enters once per 15 minutes is overtrading at the same frequency.
      </p>
      <p>
        The signal is also session-phase aware. Meridian tracks whether frequency is accelerating — not
        just elevated. An entry rate that is high but stable has different behavioral implications than
        one that is increasing mid-session under loss conditions.
      </p>

      <h2>What the PSI score reflects</h2>
      <p>
        The Overtrading Pace signal is one of seven dimensions that feed the composite Psychological Stability
        Index. An elevated Pace signal alone may produce a yellow (Caution) reading. When Pace elevation
        coincides with other active signals — Revenge Entry, Stop Manipulation, Size Spike — the composite
        score can drop to Critical even if no single indicator is at maximum severity.
      </p>
      <p>
        This composite approach is more predictive than any single signal in isolation. The behavioral
        fingerprint of an impending serious drawdown typically involves multiple indicators activating
        within the same session window, not a single dramatic event.
      </p>

      <h2>What Meridian Guard can enforce</h2>
      <p>
        For traders where overtrading is the primary failure mode, the most relevant Guard configurations are:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Trade count limit per time window</strong> — configurable maximum entries per hour or per
          session, enforced by the software rather than self-reported</li>
        <li><strong>Pace-triggered mandatory pause</strong> — Guard can block new entries when the Overtrading
          Pace signal exceeds a defined threshold, independently of the composite PSI score</li>
        <li><strong>Cooldown after consecutive losses</strong> — mandatory wait period after N consecutive
          losing trades, regardless of total session count</li>
        <li><strong>PSI-based entry restriction</strong> — when the composite score drops below a configured
          level, Guard can block entries until PSI recovers</li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        The enforcement is automatic and does not require a decision at the moment it is most needed. The
        rules are configured during a deliberate session review, when the trader is not in the state that
        the rules are designed to manage.
      </p>

      <h2>What Meridian does not do</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>Does not automatically close or reduce open positions</li>
        <li>Does not provide signals for when to trade — only for when the behavioral pattern suggests not to</li>
        <li>Does not eliminate all overtrading — it raises the structural friction around the behavior patterns
          that produce it</li>
        <li>Does not transmit trade data externally</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Use in conjunction with existing NinjaTrader controls</h2>
      <p>
        Meridian operates alongside NinjaTrader's native account risk controls. Broker-enforced maximum
        position size and account-level daily loss limits should remain active. Meridian monitors the behavioral
        layer between each individual order — the pattern of decisions that native controls cannot evaluate.
      </p>

